The fruit and their seed spreaders
Color , size and other characteristics of fruit are important on order to be identified by the dispersers of seeds .
Dr. Galetti revealed that fruit dispersed by birds are generally red or black and sweet tasting such as the pau de viola tree ( Citharexyllum mirianthum ) and the Brazil cherry ( Eugenia spp . ) , or fatty such as the nutmegs ( Virola spp . ) .
Those dispersed by mammals are almost always sweet , yellow , pungent and pithy , such as the guava ( Campomanesia spp . ) and the bakupari ( Rheedia gardneriana ) .
There are even those adapted to dispersion by ants , such as the castor bean ( Riccinus communis ) and the capixingui ( Croton floribundus ) , which have a small oily reward for the insects .
